   "answer" : "<p>Isaac Asimov wrote a lot of books. Some of them were about robots. Those books kind of serve as the grandfather of android stories in which robots are commonplace and a major influence on human societyâ¦ he coined the term âpositronicâ that you see all the time in robot media.</p><p>The âThree Laws of Roboticsâ, as youâve probably already read, are present in most of his robot stories as the foundational rules by which the âbots abide. Itâs never really clarified exactly how they work, and in some stories, they can be ignored or deprogrammed relatively easily - in others, theyâre implied to affect the core processes by which the positronic brain functions and conflicts between them can shut down a robotâs brain and/or serve as the plot of as many books as Asimov could squeeze out in a 20 year period.</p><p>The âofficialâ laws dictate, in order of importance, that 1.) a robot canât harm or passively allow harm to come to a human, 2.) if has to obey orders given to it by a human unless they conflict with the first law, and 3.) it canât allow itself to be hurt unless itâs in the service or the first or second law.</p><p>The Zeroeth Law is:Â <i>âA robot may not harm humanity, or through inaction allow humanity to come to harm.â</i> Itâs the First Law applied to humanity as a whole, and is how some of the more advanced robots provide the philosophical justification they need to prevent genocide by attacking individual assholes, as well as to step back and try to reduce humanityâs dependence upon technology in general.Â </p>",
